## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

**10 tests, 10 findings — 7 Critical, 1 High, 2 Medium**

This test class is a textbook **coverage-touching** suite. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called (achieving that 95% line coverage), but almost nothing is actually *verified*. Six tests have zero assertions, three use only `Assert.IsNotNull` (which passes even if results are wrong), and no test checks a value, count, or side-effect. These tests cannot catch regressions — they only fail if the code throws an exception.

---

### Critical Findings

#### 1. Coverage-Touching Pattern (Systemic)
**Location:** Entire class (lines 6–89)

The class walks through every public method — `AddProduct`, `GetProduct`, `UpdatePrice`, `RemoveProduct`, `Search`, `GetAll`, `GetProductCount`, `ApplyBulkDiscount`, `ExportToCsv`, `ImportFromCsv` — with no meaningful assertions. This is the canonical coverage-inflation anti-pattern.

---

#### 2. No Assertion — `AddProduct_Works` (line 17)
Calls `AddProduct` but never verifies the product was stored.

```csharp
// BEFORE (line 17-21)
public void AddProduct_Works()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);
}

// AFTER
public void AddProduct_ValidProduct_IsRetrievable()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);
    var retrieved = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual("Widget", retrieved?.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, retrieved?.Price);
}
```

---

#### 3. Trivial Assertion — `GetProduct_Works` (line 23)
`Assert.IsNotNull` passes even if the product has wrong data. Never checks Sku, Name, or Price.

```csharp
// BEFORE (line 23-29)
var result = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNotNull(result);

// AFTER
var result = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNotNull(result);
Assert.AreEqual("SKU-001", result.Sku);
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", result.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, result.Price);
```

**Same issue in `SearchProducts_Works` (line 46) and `GetAllProducts_Works` (line 55)** — both assert `IsNotNull` but never check count or content. `Search("Widget")` could return `["Gadget"]` and the test would pass.

---

#### 4. No Assertion — `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 32)
Calls `UpdatePrice` but never reads the product back to verify the price changed. A bug in the `Save(p with { Price = newPrice })` logic would go undetected.

